                <h1> Recipe of Paneer and chole: </h1>
                    <p id="para2"> Paneer and Chole (also known as Chole Paneer or Chana Paneer) is a rich, protein-packed North Indian curry that combines
                    soft paneer cubes with tender white chickpeas in a spiced tomato-onion gravy.                                          <p id="para3"> IngredientsBase: 1 cup dried white chickpeas (soaked 8+ hours) and 150–200g paneer cubes.Aromatics: 1 large onion
                    (finely chopped), 2 medium tomatoes (pureed), 1 tsp ginger-garlic paste, and 2 green chillies.Whole Spices: 1 bay leaf,
                    1 cinnamon stick, 2 black cardamoms, and 1 tsp cumin seeds.Ground Spices: 1 tsp coriander powder, 1 tsp cumin powder, 1
                    tsp red chilli powder, ½ tsp
                    turmeric, and 1 tsp garam masala.</p>                                                                                          <p id="para4" >> Finishing Touches: 1 tsp kasuri methi (dried fenugreek leaves), ½ tsp amchur (mango powder), and fresh coriander for garnish.🥣 Step-by-Step InstructionsPrepare the Chickpeas: Pressure cook the soaked chickpeas with 3 cups of water and salt for 10–12 whistles until soft. For a darker colour and deeper flavour, add a tea bag or dried amla to the cooker.Sauté the Paneer: Lightly fry the paneer cubes in a little oil or ghee until goldenbrown. </p>                                                                <p id="para5"> Optional: Soak the fried paneer in warm water for 5 minutes to keep it soft.Make the Masala: Heat 2 tbsp oil in a
                    pan. Sauté cumin seeds and whole spices until fragrant. Add onions and fry until golden brown, then stir in the
                    ginger-garlic paste.Cook the Gravy: Add tomato puree and cook until the oil starts to separate from the masala. Mix in
                    all the ground spices (turmeric, chilli, coriander, and cumin powders) and sauté for a minute.Simmer: Add the cooked
                    chickpeas along with their stock. Bring to a boil and simmer for 5–8 minutes. Mash a few chickpeas with the back of your
                    turmeric, and 1 tsp garam masala.</p>
